Beautiful church which cannot be seen from afar because it is embedded in the surrounding buildings, unless you come from Rue du Lateran, where you can see from afar the pediment with a fresco of the three archangels and the child Jesus.  It was formerly the chapel of the college of Beauvais (known as "de Dormans", architect Raymond du Temple), built in 1380.  The interior is very peaceful and prayerful. The iconostasis is magnificent, there are beautiful icons and stained glass windows. It seems to me that the church is only open on Sundays for services, but I beg to be wrong.  I recommend visiting it for a time of prayer.
Very beautiful little Orthodox church in a pleasant neighborhood!!!

In the heart of the Latin Quarter, not far from Notre Dame de Paris (but on the left bank of the Seine - rive gauche) and a stone's throw from Saint Julien le Pauvre (the oldest church in Paris), the Romanian Orthodox Church "Holy Archangels Michael, Gavriil and Rafail", is, along with the Russian one in Daru street and the Greek one in Bizet street, one of the three Orthodox cathedrals in the [historical] City of Lights.  With services in the Romanian language and a Romanian clergy, the church in Jean de Beauvais Street represents an oasis of Romanianness and Orthodoxy for all Romanians, whether they are exiles, political or social refugees, students or simple tourists.  Starting with May 10, 2009, the parish becomes an integral part of the Mother Church again, coming under the patronage of Metropolitan Iosif, of the Romanian Orthodox Metropolitanate for Western and Southern Europe.  You are welcome to church services and prayers, as well as to other cultural and educational events in the life of the parish!

The church itself and its impressive history. Beautiful choir. BUT when it comes to organization during services, it is a DISASTER. DURING THE LITURGY, SOMETHING IS UNDERSTOOD ONLY IN THE FACE. OTHERWISE, people talk, it's a constant bustle, they stay in one place for 5 minutes, then come back, if the children don't take me for a walk to calm down, etc. In conclusion, from the middle of the church in the back you can't understand anything and you can't concentrate on the service. It's an atmosphere like at the MARKET. PEOPLE WHO DRESS UP and stand around, especially during the sermon. THE PRIEST IS SPEAKING, THE PEOPLE ARE SPEAKING. If you want to find peace of mind, this is not the right place. Church staff should discipline their parishioners. And to educate them why they come to church and how people should behave. I'm curious how Saint Ion Gura de Aur would have reacted to such a commotion... About hygiene during a pandemic... I won't say anymore. People who touch cult objects with BOTH HANDS, do not respect social distance, half-worn masks, etc. MOURNING.
